post_cb({"25152260": {"CommentCount": "1", "ViewCount": "62", "CreationDate": "2014-08-06T04:30:14.610", "LastActivityDate": "2014-08-06T04:30:14.610", "Title": "Sequence in an array of narrow character type", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "25152260", "Score": "1", "Body": "<p>The following definition of a <code>tracable pointer object</code> is provided in the N3797 standard (sec. 3.7.4.3/1):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_25152260_25152260_0\">A traceable pointer object is </p>\n<p id=\"so_25152260_25152260_1\">[...]</p>\n<p id=\"so_25152260_25152260_2\">\u2014 a sequence of elements in an\n  array of narrow character type (3.9.1), where the size and alignment\n  of the sequence match those of some object pointer type.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It isn't simple for me to understand the restriction and I would like to look at the <strong>real example</strong> of such <code>tracable pointer object</code>. Could you possibly provide it? I general I have a doubt about alignment. As I can see with <code>alignof</code>, the alignment of <code>char</code> is <code>1</code>, but alignment of any pointer to type is <code>8</code>...</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><arrays><pointers>", "OwnerUserId": "2786156", "AnswerCount": "0"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_25152260_25152260_2": {"section_id": 7184, "quality": 0.9411764705882353, "length": 16}}, "n3337": {"so_25152260_25152260_2": {"section_id": 6928, "quality": 0.8823529411764706, "length": 15}}, "n4659": {"so_25152260_25152260_2": {"section_id": 8692, "quality": 0.9411764705882353, "length": 16}}}});